&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]The Children’s Society[bold]&#xa0;[bold]About The Children’s Society[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Children’s Society supports nearly 50,000 children and young people every year through our specialist 
[normal]services and children’s centres. We believe in achieving a better childhood for every child but have a particular focus on children who have nowhere else to turn, such as children living in poverty, young refugees, children at risk on the streets, disabled
[normal] children and children in trouble with the law. We seek to give a voice to children and young people and influence policy and practice so they have a better chance in life.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We believe that every child has the right to a decent home that their family can a
[normal]fford. We welcome the opportunity to raise our concerns with the committee about the impact that reforms to housing support in the welfare system could have on this.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]This submission focuses on the following three key areas of reform:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1. Local Housing Allowance (LHA) 
[normal]reforms
[normal]2. The household benefit cap
[normal]3. Localisation of support with housing costs
[normal]4. Housing support in Universal Credit
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Key issues:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1. Local Housing Allowance (LHA) reforms[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Housing Benefit for clai
[normal]mants in the private rental sector has gone through a period of radical change:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As a result of a combination of these changes, if rental prices rise rapidly, prices will increasingly 
[normal]draw away from eligible rents for LHA purposes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 1: Shortfall between LHA eligible rent (English average[bold]) and actual expected rent 2010-2013[bold], by size of property[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The losses are greatest for larger families. A low income
[normal] family with four or more children requiring a four bedroom property  in private rental accommodation can expect to see a shortfall of £24 per week (£1250 per year) as a result of changes to LHA entitlements between 2010 and 2013.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For a family in a three 
[normal]bedroom home, between 2010 and 2013, the average eligible rent of a private rental property has fallen by around £8 per week. Over the same period
[normal], we would have expected rents to have risen by £6 per week. This would leave a £14 per week shortfall betwee
[normal]n eligible rents and actual expected rental prices – around £730 per year.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This is shown in the table below. Clearly, the change from the 50
[normal]th
[normal] to 30
[normal]th
[normal] percentile of local rents had a major impact in 2011. However, since then, the gap has continued to widen as a result of LHA rates rising more slowly than private rents.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 2: Eligible rent and expected rent for three bedroom property (English avera[bold]ge) 2010-2013[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is notable that the government did not expect changes to LHA entitlement to increase eligible rents with inflation rather than local rents, to create behavioural change, given the costs of moving home.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“No beha
[normal]vioural impact is assumed over the forecast period as differences in rents will be small in the early years compared to the transaction costs of moving. The current estimate of the anticipated reduction in benefit expenditure is in the order of £400m in 20
[normal]14/15 (real terms, 2012/13 prices).”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We are concerned that that given the costs of moving home and the lack of availability of affordable private rental properties, many families will reduce disposable income as a consequence of reductions in their LHA 
[normal]payments. This means that money intended to cover the costs of living is needed to cover shortfalls in assistance with housing costs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Given the evidence that private rental prices are increasing faster than Housing Benefit rates, it is unsurprising that i
[normal]t is becoming increasingly common for families to become homeless as a result of Assured Shorthold Tenancies ending and not being renewed.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The table below shows the number of households accepted as being owed a main homelessness duty by their local auth
[normal]ority, who lost their last home as a result of the end of an Assured Shorthold Tenancy. The number have nearly tripled since 2010.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 3: households accepted as owed a main homelessness duty by the Local Authority who lost their last home as a result o[bold]f the end of an Assured Shorthold Tenancy: 2010-2013[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As private sector housing is becoming increasingly unaffordable, access to social housing is also becoming increasingly limited. Numbers of households on social housing waiti
[normal]ng lists has increased by more than 800,000 since 1997, including a rise of around 100,000 since 2010 (see figure 4). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 4: Local Authorities’ housing waiting lists 1997-2012[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]It is crucial that the lowest income families a
[normal]re able to afford the cost of their home. We are concerned that for those families on the very lowest incomes the increasing gaps between eligible rents for Housing Benefit and private rents, combined with increasing inaccessibility of social housing are t
[normal]ogether making housing unaffordable for many families with children. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]During a recent debate in the House of Lords regarding linking the uprating of local LHA rates to CPI, Lord Freud committed to review the situation if local allowance rates and rents 
[normal]become out of step
[normal].
[normal]Recommendation 1: The government should commit to a review of the affordability of private rental sector accommodation following reforms to LHA since 2011. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2. The household benefit cap[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The household benefit cap applies a maximum 
[normal]benefit entitlement of £500 per week for most out of work families with children. Housing Benefit entitlement is reduced in order to reduce household entitlement to this limit
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The following table shows how the income of families in private rental housin
[normal]g after the cap is applied, may compare to the poverty line for their household
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 5. Disposable income after cap applied for out of work couple with average private rental sector rent for relevant property sizes[bold], and varying numbers of children. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Average PRS rental prices[bold]Disposable income after cap applied[bold]Poverty line (after housing costs deducted)[bold]1 child
[normal]£146
[normal]£196
[normal]£272
[normal]2 children
[normal]£175
