[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For families with 4 or more children with an average private rental sector rent, benefit levels fall increasingly far below the poverty line as a result of the cap. For families with 5 or more children, their income after housing costs could be less than 
[normal]5
[normal]0%
[normal] of the poverty line.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Suggestions have been made that the level of the cap be further reduced – one MP suggested a cap of £17000 (£327 per week). This would reduce disposable incomes after the cap is applied still further.
[normal] A couple
[normal] with four or more chi
[normal]ldren 
[normal]c
[normal]ould have their disposable income limited to around £91 per week
[normal] (about £2 per person per day)
[normal] –
[normal] with which they would need to cover all of their household needs, including food, clothes, transport and utilities.  T
[normal]his is less than 20% of the income
[normal] they would need to be lifted out of poverty.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Figure 5. Disposable income after cap applied (out of work couple with average private rental sector rent for a relevant property size, and varying numbers of children) compared to poverty line for each [bold]household size.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The benefit cap is already having severe consequences for households in the private rental sector, including households who succeed in making the move into work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]One The Children’s Society family support worker s
[normal]upporting a family affected by the benefit cap told us:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“The family have been served a section 21 notice as a result of their inability to pay full rent.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] They have been awarded a discretionary housing payment however there is still a shortfall.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The family is large - 5 children - and have lost £92 pound a week
[normal] with the introduction of the cap.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Since the introduction of the cap mum has got herself a part time job of 16 hours which now means she comes off of the benefit cap and can now reapply for housing benefit to assist.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] They are still being evicted though 
[normal]as they have already gone into arrears.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We welcome the Government’s assurances that they will monitor the impact of the benefit cap and review it in 2014 following its first year of operation.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Recommendation 2: Given that around three quarters of those affected by the cap are children, it is particularly important that the review pays specific regard to the impact of the benefit cap on the well-being of children.  It is important that as part of[bold] this the review considers – [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3. Localisation of support with housing costs[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Increasingly, support with housing costs is determined on a l
[normal]ocal, and discretionary basis. Local authorities have been provided with additional funding for Discretionary Housing Payments (DHP) to help deal with difficult cases caused by reforms, such as the benefit cap. Additionally, following the abolition of part
[normal]s of the discretionary Social Fund, local authorities have been allocated resources to introduce local welfare assistance schemes to provide support for families.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]i. Discretionary Housing Payments [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In 2010/11 £20 million was available to local authorit
[normal]ies for DHP, this was increased to £30 million in 2011/2012 and £60 m illion in 2012/2013.  The 2013/14 allocation included an additional £30 million and £65 million to address the social rented sector size criteria and the benefit cap respectively, as wel
[normal]l as £5 million to support the most sparsely populated areas. In 2014/15 The DHP pot available will be £125 million.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Figure 6: Discretionary Housing Payment funding (Great Britain) 2010-2015[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Clearly, local authorities have been given considerably more scope to address families housing needs on a local basis. The challenge is to ensure that this support gets to those families who need this most. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Recommendation 3: The Department for Work and P[bold]ensions could do more to assist local authorities in advertising their schemes.[bold] 
[normal]The gov.uk website should host links to all local DHP schemes in order to ensure that people looking to find out about their local scheme are able to find this online.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Local A[bold]uthorities should ensure that family information services are effectively communicating information about their local DHP scheme.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]ii. The introduction of local welfare assistance schemes[bold]From April 2013, crisis loans for living expenses and community 
[normal]care grants were abolished. Instead, funding was provided for local authority administered welfare assistance schemes.
[normal]Our recent report 
[normal]Nowhere to turn
[normal] 
[normal]examined the local emergency and community support now available through local welfare assistance sche
[normal]mes. We found that the vast majority of the schemes are providing support for similar needs that were covered by crisis loans and community care grants. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A significant exception is that some schemes have stated that they will not be providing rent in adva
[normal]nce. For example, Medway council states that their local welfare provision is scheme is “
[normal]not a rent deposit scheme or a rent in advance scheme
[normal]” and Buckingham council’s
[normal] scheme also states it does not provide this support.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We are concerned that the areas 
[normal]where local welfare schemes do not provide support for rent in advance, families will find it more difficult to access permanent housing and this could lead to increased homelessness. Research from Crisis found that 69% of housing advisors who work in priv
[normal]ate rented housing access schemes have used crisis loans to fund rent in advance. As one housing adviser who responded to the Crisis survey said: “
[normal]Crisis loans are absolutely vital in enabling clients to source rent in advance
[normal]”. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Recommendation 4: Local w[bold]elfare assistance schemes should make provision for rent in advance.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Our 
[normal]Nowhere to turn 
[normal]report also found that the majority of local schemes had some form of residency or local connection entitlement criteria. Around half of schemes indicated that the 
[normal]claimant needed to be resident within the borough. In three stricter cases claimants had to have been resident for at least a year before they could apply for help.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Figure 7: Local welfare assistance eligibility – residency criteria[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Reforms to housing 
[normal]benefit in both the private and social rented sectors are likely to lead to more low income households moving home and area. Our concern is that families will not be eligible for support through local welfare assistance schemes if they have to move to area
[normal]s with strict residency criteria. Only a small number of local welfare assistance schemes allowed claimants to apply for assistance if they were moving into the area or if they had a local connection, such as family living there. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Some schemes had excepti
[normal]ons to residency criteria such as families fleeing domestic violence, care leavers housed outside the local area or homeless households, but this was not universal. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Recommendation 5: Local authorities should not set extended periods of residency before [bold]households can get access to local welfare assistance.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Recommendation 6: Exemptions from residency cr[bold]iteria should be established,[bold] specified[bold] and transparently communicated[bold] for all local welfare assistance schemes.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]4. Housing support in Universal Credit[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Support with housing costs is radically changing as a result of the introduction of Universal Credit. Help with housing costs is rolled into the provision of other support. This will mean that a significant additional cohort of middle income renting famili
[normal]es will receive support with housing costs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For example, a single parent family with two children and with eligible rent of £100 per week would stop being entitled to Housing Benefit when the parent earned £395 per week (£20500 per year) or more. Under Un
[normal]iversal Credit, they will continue to be entitled to receive some help with their rental costs with an income of up to around £655 per week (£34000 per year).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The introduction of Universal Credit will raise a number of challenges made all the more importa
[normal]nt as a result of the increased cohort of claimants receiving help with their housing costs. This section will consider three issues in particular: 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]i. Variations in work allowances by levels of housing cost[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]It has always been intended that under Universal Credit, households would have different levels of work allowances depending on whether they have housing costs. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, initally, DWP stated there would be different levels of allowance for households wit
[normal]h and without housing costs, with the level of "maximum" allowance reduced by 1.5 x the level of housing costs claimed, until it reached a "minimum" level.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]So, for example, the "maximum" allowance for a lone parent with two children would be £8,800 per ye
[normal]ar, and the minimum would be £3,150.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, UC regulations now provide for only a maximum level of work allowance (for households without housing costs), and a minimum level (for those with housing costs). We are concerned this measure actually makes th
[normal]e system considerably more complicated, since households with low levels of housing costs in receipt of UC would have to make a determination of whether they would be better off claiming for help with housing costs but receiving a reduced earnings disregar
[normal]d, or making no claim for help with housing costs. For example:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Recommendation 7: There should be a minimum and maximum level of disregard, with the maximum reduced by 1.5 x the rate of housing costs until they reach the minimum d[bold]isregard.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]ii. Housing costs for owner-occupiers[bold]As with the current system, Universal Credit makes some provision for help with housing costs for home owners. We are very concerned by the "zero earnings rule" to be introduced within the Support for 
[normal]Mortgage Interest (SMI) regulations which mean that SMI can only be applied where the household is undertaking no paid work
[normal].  This is considerably less generous than the current system where the attachment of SMI to out of work income replacement benefits
[normal] means that households may receive support on working up to 16, or in some cases 24, hours per week.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The regulations note that for those attempting part-time work, the removal of SMI will "
[normal]in part be compensated by the operation of the full disregard
[normal]".  H
[normal]owever, for households undertaking very small amounts of paid work this compensation will be extremely limited, or non-existent.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Many parents attempt part time work to keep labour market skills up to date and as a route back into long term employment, for
[normal] example, parents who are disabled and are considering making a move back into work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This new rule risks creating great complexity in accepting money for any period of employment, and creates an enormous “cliff edge” of entitlement.  In the worst cases, c
[normal]laimants may find that they lose very significant amounts of money as a result of taking on a couple of hours of work, and as a result losing their SMI entitlement.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Recommendation 8: Households earning up to the level of their maximum earnings disregard s[bold]hould be entitled to receive SMI payments as part of their Universal Credit claim[bold].  [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]iii. Direct payment to tenants[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Under Universal Credit, payments for housing costs will normally be paid directly to the tenant (rather than to the landlord). This will
[normal] be a significant change for many households living in the social rented sector who currently have payments made to their landlord.
[normal]The government believes this will promote financial capability and independence. However, we are concerned that some familie
[normal]s with children may struggle to manage their rental payments.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]One survey
[normal] found that 86% of social tenants believe “strongly” that it is better for housing benefit to be paid direct to the landlord and 35% were not confident that they can keep up rental p
[normal]ayments if they receive their rent direct.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The direct payments demonstration project has been established in six areas across Britain. In May, 17% of the total claimants had had their payments switched back to their landlord
[normal].
[normal]Additionally, concerns have
[normal] been raised in the project review that the outcomes achieved within the pilot areas required resource intensive interventions and may not be scalable following the roll out of Universal Credit
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The government do acknowledge that some households will req
[normal]uire alternative payment arrangements (APAs) for payment of housing costs. The current guidance on the application of APAs specifies two tiers of problem which would indicate claimants that are “highly likely” and those that are “less likely” to require al
[normal]ternative payments
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Recommendation 9: Claimants with a history of rent arrears, those with current rent arrears[bold], and families that have previously been homeless should be considered “highly likely” to require APAs for their housing costs.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Recommendation 10: The Local Support Services Framework for Universal Credit needs to ensure that sufficient support is provided to enable resource-intensive interventions from local delivery partners, to identify families that may require housing payments[bold] made direct to landlords.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]27 September 2013[bold]&#xa0;
[normal] 30% of the savings will be used to exempt areas where prices rise the fastest.
